The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, March 18, 2004 				 Berger considers splitting shares 
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, March 17: Nine days after it obtained shareholders approval to a bonus issue, Berger Paints today announced that its shares with a paid-up value of Rs 10 will be split into five. Both moves are aimed at increasing the liquidity of the companys shares.																								If the proposal is approved in the extra-ordinary general meeting to be held on April 19, the paid-up value of Bergers shares will come down to Rs 2. Thanks to the 1:2 bonus issue, Bergers free float  or shares in trade  will be going up from 91 lakh to 1.36 crore. The split will further increase it to 6.8 crore. Berger will have an equity base of 3.98 crore shares, of which the promoters own 65.7 per cent.																								The price of Bergers shares rose by Rs 4.80 to Rs 205.90 on the National Stock Exchange today. It advanced 2.39 per cent from its previous close, while Nifty  the broad market index of 50 key stocks  registered a 0.03 per cent gain. The stock has been on a roll for the last one year, gaining more than 200 per cent  it was trading between Rs 60 and Rs 65 a year ago.																								However, the price of Bergers share is likely to fall once the bonus shares are allotted to shareholders. The record date for allotment of bonus shares is March 24. Berger obtained shareholders approval to the bonus issue at an extraordinary general meeting on March 8.																								Earlier this month, the company also announced its plan to enter the financial services business in partnership with Principal, Punjab National Bank and Vijaya Bank. The Calcutta-based paints major will own 25 per cent stake in two firms: one will manage pension funds and the other will hawk insurance policies.																								Explaining the decision to foray into financial services, Berger had said it had surplus cash that it wanted to invest. The 25 per cent stake in the two firms will cost Rs 30 crore. Berger will invest Rs 1.5 crore in the insurance brokerage firm, and Rs 28.5 crore in the pension fund management business. 																								Unveiling his plans to expand the paints business, Berger chairman Kuldip Singh Dhingra had said earlier this month that the company was planning to enter the countries neighbouring India and those in South East Asia.
